synopses.synopsis: Casey, Crime Photographer had more history than substance. It was a B-grade radio detective show, on a par perhaps with The Falcon, better than Mr. Keen, but lacking the polish and style of Sam Spade. Often a picture snapped at a crime scene led Casey to play detective. At the Blue Note Cafe, the crowd was friendly and the music was more than a backdrop. The jazz piano belonged to Herman Chittison; occasionally the music was by Teddy Wilson, noted alumnus of the Benny Goodman trio. Casey was also an early TV item, seen live on CBS, 1951?ÃÂ³?ÃÂ©ÃÂ¼?ÃÂÃÂ£52. Jan Miner and John Gibson made the transition from radio, though Gibson was soon replaced. Richard Carlyle and Darren McGavin played Casey on television. - On the Air: The Encyclopedia of Old-Time Radio by John Dunning
